In [[law]], the '''last injurious exposure rule''' is the principle that when an [[occupational disease]] was caused by a succession of jobs, or could have been caused by any one of a succession of jobs, the most recent employer with the [[risk]] exposure is [[liable]].<ref name="Oran">{{cite book | last = Oran | first = Daniel| authorlink = Daniel Oran | title = Oran's Dictionary of the Law (West Legal Studies), 4th Edition | publisher = Delmar Cengage Learning |date=June 2007 | location = Florence, KY | pages =  | isbn = 1-4180-8091-8}}</ref>

